How to Use systemd Timers Instead of Cron in Debian 12 Bookworm
    https://www.siberoloji.com/how-to-use-systemd-timers-instead-of-cron-in-debian-12-bookworm/
        - $ systemctl list-timers                           //to see the active timers
        - $ systemctl status wall-broadcast.timer           // check timer status
        - $ sudo systemctl start wall-broadcast.service     //test script
        - # on changes:
            $ sudo systemctl daemon-reload
            # if [Install] section changed
                - $ sudo systemctl enable wall-broadcast.timer
            sudo systemctl restart wall-broadcast.timer     //restart the timer
        - to stop it:
            sudo systemctl stop wall-broadcast.timer            //stop for this run but will execute again on the boot
            sudo systemctl disable --now wall-broadcast.timer   // now stops it immediately and prevent execution on reboot
        - $ man 5 systemd.timer
        - Use descriptive unit names and place them in /etc/systemd/system/
            or ~/.config/systemd/user/ (for user context)
Understanding Systemd Units and Unit Files: 
